Navigate to other release versions of Doxee Platform Template Designer

[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/template-designer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/template-designer-6-7)

This chapter lists the general actions which are available in Template Designer via menu entries, toolbar, context menus or shortcuts. For each action the available ways of using it are mentioned.

## File
### New Template
**Usage: **Menu, Toolbar, *CTRL+N*

- Creates a new Infinica file:

- Infinica Template

- Infinica Page Master Package

- Infinica Template Part Package

- Infinica Style Package

- Infinica Metadata Package

These various types do not differ by their file type, but by their Output Configurations (see ![](data:image/png;base64,) [Output Configurations](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1-1#output-configurations)). All Infinica templates and packages have the common file type .itx.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 1. File &gt; New Template*

You can either create a new blank template of the type you choose, or you create a new template from a master template (see [Master Templates](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-master-templates-1)).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 2. Choose file type*

### Open
**Usage: **Menu, *CTRL+O*

Opens a file dialog to choose the file to open.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 3. File &gt; Open File*

A dialog opens that allows accessing the local file system as well as remote file systems, like the Doxee Content Repository. The available hosts are listed under the node Registered Hosts. When the desired host is not listed new hosts can be added by right clicking at Registered Hosts &gt; Configure Hosts. For more information see [Resource Explorer](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-actions-1-1#resource-explorer1).

### Close
**Usage**: Menu, *CTRL+W*

Closes the active file. Clicking on the ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAoAAAAKCAIAAAACUFjqAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAYklEQVQYlX1QQQ6AMAgri3/iTZDsNUv4E6+ahypOTdYTtEAbxMwAAIgI3HB3Fg3AUB2qRbk7GQBHbdQEBULmnBzHGz0zIhpde+Zfu7w3aJVlZSuHmFlptFjb5zj9Pjlk/5YTjFY2A7f/K4IAAAAASUVORK5CYII=) of the current tab performs the same action.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 4. Close active file*

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 7. Save active file*

**Usage**: Menu

Opens a file dialog to save the current template elsewhere.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 8. Save file as*

### Save All
**Usage**: Menu, Toolbar, *CTRL+SHIFT+S*

Saves all open files.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 9. Save all open files*

### Import
**Usage**: Menu

Offers the following options:

##### Import RTF Files
opens a file dialog to choose an existing RTF file to import into Doxee Template Designer.

##### Import FO Files
opens a file dialog to choose an existing XSL-FO file to import into Doxee Template Designer.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 10. Import files*

### Export
**Usage**: Menu

Offers the following options:

##### Text file
exports the active file as a text file. Note: Only the text components are exported and no other elements or styles.

##### XSL:FO file
exports the active file as an XSL-FO-conform XSL-file. This is the file that is used at runtime by the Doxee Process Engine to create documents from your templates.

##### FO file
exports the active file as an FO file, by generating an XSL-FO file internally and running the XSL transformation on the associated XML sample.

##### **XSL:IDX file**
exports the active file as an XSL-IDX file, which resembles the transformation of the template to IDX.

##### IDX file
exports the active file as an IDX file, by running the XSL-IDX transformation on the associated XML sample. An IDX file is a file type that is used by Doxee Composer to display documents. More information can be found in the Doxee Composer User Guide.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 11. Export file*

## Edit
### Print
**Usage**: Toolbar

Opens a dialog for printing the content of the active file.

### Undo
**Usage**: Menu, Toolbar, Context Menu, *CTRL+Z*

Performs a simple undo.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 12. Edit &gt; Undo*

### Redo
**Usage**: Menu, Toolbar, Context Menu, *CTRL+Y*

Performs a simple redo.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 13. Edit &gt; Redo*

### Cut
**Usage**: Menu, Toolbar, *CTRL+X*

The selected element(s) is/are cut and available in the clipboard for a paste action. The content in the clipboard is available until cut or copy is performed again.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 14. Edit &gt; Cut*

### Copy
**Usage**: Menu, Toolbar, *CTRL+C*

The selected element(s) is/are copied to the clipboard and available for a paste action. The content in the clipboard is available until cut or copy is performed again.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 15. Edit &gt; Copy*

### Paste
**Usage**: Menu, Toolbar, *CTRL+V*

The last copied/cut element(s) is/are pasted to the current cursor position if the position is valid for the copied/cut element.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 16. Edit &gt; Paste*

### Delete
**Usage**: Menu, *DELETE*

The currently selected element(s) is/are deleted.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 17. Edit &gt; Delete*

### Select All
**Usage**: Menu, *CTRL+A*

The whole content of the template, i.e. all elements are selected.

### Preferences
**Usage**: Menu

Doxee Template Designer preferences are displayed, which will be described in the following section.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 19. Edit &gt; Preferences*

#### Composer Previews
In the section Composer Previews the embedded composer preview for Template Designer can be configured. A composer preview will display the document using an external Composer installation in an embedded web browser. This allows the user to verify the layout of the document in Composer, and also to test Composer-specific features like insertion points, and editable/read-only and visible/hidden areas of the document.

For Composer preview to work properly, Template Designer and Composer must have access to the same template and sample XML files. This can be a directory on the local disk for a locally installed Composer (in most cases specifically for the Composer preview) or a file share on a remote server, that also Composer accesses for templates.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 20. Edit &gt; Preferences &gt; Composer Previews*

Columns:

##### Label
This label is displayed as text on the preview tab in the editor window.

##### Base URI
This is the absolute path to the Composer that is used for preview. Template Designer will append all necessary additional query parameters, such as paths to the template and the sample data files.

##### Data directory
Composer preview will be available for all templates that are opened from within this data directory or any of its subdirectories. This data directory must be the same as the template base directory that is configured in Composer, although Composer may access the same directory under a different path, especially if it is running on a server.

![](data:image/png;base64,) *Figure 21. Edit &gt; Preferences &gt; Composer Previews &gt; Edit*

After the Composer Preview is configured and a template from the chosen data directory is opened, the Composer preview tab with the specified label will be available in the editor.

#### Dependencies
In the section Dependencies the Dependency View can be configured, which lets the user navigate dependencies and references between files, such as uses of template parts in several different templates.

This feature works by indexing the relationships between files and storing them in a database. In this section the storage location for the database and the directories to be indexed are defined.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 22. Edit &gt; Preferences &gt; Dependencies*

> Important

Please have patience after performing changes to the list of indexed directories right after they are added (or in case you perform a re-indexing). Since the re-indexing starts immediately and will take some time.

#### External Calls
In the section External Calls custom menus with own functions can be created.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 23. Edit &gt; Preferences &gt; External Calls*

The column Label holds the name of the menu tree, submenus are separated by a slash (/). The example above creates a menu point Preview with the functions ODT-Label and RTF- Label.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 24. Preview ODT-/RTF-Label*

Selecting one of the menu items, the registered bat-file or the command is executed.

#### FO
In the section FO, renderer settings can be changed, i.e. FOP can be assigned a configuration file, which is necessary to use custom fonts. Alternative renderers such as XMLMind (XFC), XEP or IBEX can be installed, activated and adjusted in the FO settings dialog as well. The FO preview can be activated, as well as the preview with assertions (see ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAQAAAAPCAYAAADDNm69AAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAWklEQVQImWP8OJlhAgMDgwEDBFxggXLsoQIMTAxogImBgeEDEv8BEwMDwwV0AQwtlAqwMDAwLGBgYDiA7FIBBgaGBKjABBYGBoYJDAinK2A1I4GBgaEAqrUBABADDKrrGXQyAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) [Assertion](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-elements-1-1#assertion)).

The last option controls whether the PDF preview will be opened within Template Designer or in an external application. Due to a problem between Adobe Acrobat PDF Reader, Java, and Windows 10, the PDF Reader tends to crash after a few previews and takes Template Designer with it. As a counter-measure, Template Designer will deactivate this option by default when it detects that it is running on Windows 10.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 25. Edit &gt; Preferences &gt; FO*

#### Resource Explorer
Resource Explorer appears every time a resource is saved or loaded in form of a file selec- tion dialog, but there is also a separate Resource Explorer view, which can be opened via the menu View &gt; Explorer. These settings affect both, the behaviour of the file selection dialog, as well as the Resource Explorer view.

The main preferences node Resource Explorer is shown below and holds the setting for the length of the history. This describes the maximum number of steps the button Back is allowed to go back when navigating with the Resource Explorer.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 28. Resource Explorer settings*

In the preferences node Resource Explorer &gt; Columns you can configure the displayed columns as shown below. By default columns for file name, modification date, file type and file size are displayed. Here you can modify those and add additional ones if you like. You are also allowed to define columns for user defined properties, which may be defined on resources in the Doxee Content Repository. The preference page offers the following possibilities:

- Add: Allows the definition of additional columns. In the dialog which comes up once the Add button is pressed you can set the following:

Label: Defines the name of the new column.

- Namespace: If you want to refer to an Doxee Content Repository property you have to set its namespace here, e.g. [http://www.infinica.com/jcr/demo](http://www.infinica.com/jcr/demo)

- Property: The actual name of the property which should be displayed. A list of known properties from which you can select is already predefined. In this case you dont need to define a namespace yourself. If you want to add a custom property which is used in the Doxee Content Repository, you can define it here yourself. Make sure to have the correct namespace defined then.

- Type: The data type of the property value. Here you can choose between String, Date/Time, Size and Number. This setting is mainly used when Resource Explorer is supposed to sort by this column.

- Edit: Edits a selected column so you can re-define it.

- Delete: Deletes a selected column.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 29. Resource Explorer column configuration*

In the preferences node Resource Explorer &gt; Hosts you can configure repositories, like the Doxee Content Repository, which can be accessed later via the node Registered Hosts in Resource Explorer. As seen below the following actions are available here:

- Add: Allows adding an URL to a repository. If you click this, you will be prompted for the following information in the upcoming dialog:

Label: Here you can choose the name for the new connection.

- URL: Insert the repository address here.

- User and Password: The credentials which will be used for authentication when accessing the URL. These fields are not mandatory. If you dont input your

credentials here, Resource Explorer will prompt you for them every time it needs them.

- Edit: Allows editing a selected host.

- Delete: Deletes a selected host.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 30. Configuring Resource Explorer hosts*

#### Versioning
**![](data:image/png;base64,)***Figure 32. Versioning*

This setting defines how Doxee Template Designer handles opening versioned and checked in files. The following scenarios are possible:

- Always: Files that are opened are always checked out.

- Ask: For every file, ask the user, if the file should be checked out.

- Never: Files are never checked out automatically.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 33. Checked in file*

When opening files the status of a file is tested. If the file is checked in the user is asked what to do:

- Yes, check out the file. This will grant you exclusive write access to the file. When a file is checked out the write access for other users is prohibited. Other users can only read this file and are unable to store changes. If you want to change a file it is recommended to check it out.

- No, leave the file checked in. Other users may modify the file while you have it open. If a file is checked in it can be viewed and changed by other users. If you only want to view a file without doing changes you should leave it checked in.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 34. Checked out file*

When the user has changed a checked out file he is asked what to do, when he wants to save the file:

- Yes, check the file in, creating a new version for all users to see.

- No, leave the file checked out. I am not done yet. The file stays checked out. Use this when you want to change the file again later. If you change your mind, you can still check it in without further changes.

- Revert the checkout. All modifications since the last checkout will be discarded! All changes are not saved and are discarded. Jump back to the last checked in version.

When the user opens a checked in file without checking it out the file is opened in read only

mode. The user is able to change the checked in file. If he tries to save the file a message with an error description appears:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 35. Replace file*

To save this file with a different name chose No and then Save as. To save the file with this name it is necessary to confirm with Yes. If it is still not possible to save the file you get a message window. The details of the reason are shown when you click on the *Details &gt;&gt; *button:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 36. Unable to save file*

The following properties are shown:

- Writeable

The state writeable shows if a file is generally possible to write this file. Possible states are:

The file is writeable.

- The file is not writeable.

- Lockstatus

Shows if a file is locked by a different user.

The file is locked.

If a file is locked the owner of the lock is shown.

- The file is not locked.

- Versioning

Shows if a file is versioned or not versioned.

The file is versioned.

- The file is not versioned.

- Checkin-status

 Shows if a file is currently checked in.

The file is checked in.

- The file is checked out.

The user can choose between the following actions:

- &lt; &lt; Details

Removes the details.

- Refresh

Refreshes the window.

- Change target

- Retry

Tries to save again.

- Cancel

Aborts the attempt to save.

- Checkout

Check the file out to do the saving.

- Steal lock

The Steal lock button allows the user to steal the lock from the owner of the lock. Note that special privileges are required for this action.

#### Preview Processes
![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 37. Preview processes*

It is possible to create a document preview by calling an external Infinica process and have it return the document. This is useful for projects where the rendering process does any kind of post-processing after rendering the document. By using a preview process, the end result of the process can be previewed.

The following settings define a preview process:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 38. New Preview Process*

- Enabled: Activate the checkbox to activate the preview. This allows the user to deactivate the preview temporarily without deleting all the settings.

- Name: A user defined name for the preview tab in the editor.

- Engine: Path to the rendering engine.

- Process Path: Path to the process definition within the engine.

- Renderer: Renderer to be used. This is a plain text value that is passed to the preview process as parameter "target.renderer". This allows you to create a single preview process for different renderers. Pre-defined renderers are:

fop

- xfc

- xep

- Format: Desired output format. This is a plain text value that is passed to the preview process as parameter "target.format" and "type". This allows you to create a single preview process for different document formats.

##### Pre-defined output formats are
- pdf

- docx

- rtf

- odt

- ps

- html

- assert

Your preview process should handle the following inputs:

- xsl: the XSL stylesheet that is generated from the Infinica template; pass it on to the xslTransformer activity; This input is mandatory, all other inputs should be declared optional.

- xml: the main XML data input for the xslTransformer activity, which corresponds to the no-name DataInput of your template if there is one, or to the generated metadata XML

- baseUri: the base URI that is used to resolve relative paths; It is the parent directory of the Infinica template.

- templateUri: the URI to the Infinica template

- _infinica_metadata: the generated metadata XML

- type: the requested document type of the preview

- target.format (deprecated, for compatibility): the requested document type of the preview

- target.renderer: the renderer to be used

- one more input per DataInput element in your Infinica template: pass them on to the xslTransformer activity

Your preview process should provide the following outputs:

- document: the generated document; provide one of these data types: stream, bytes, string (base64-encoded bytes); This output is expected unless there was an error, all other inputs should be considered optional.

- xslResult: the (intermediate) result of the XSL transformation, typically an FO document

- xslMessages: messages that were written during the XSL transformation via xsl:message element

- xslErrors: errors that occurred during the XSL transformation

- rendererMessages: messages that were written during the rendering step, e.g. as logs

- rendererErrors: errors that occurred during the rendering step

- mimetype: type of the generated document if it differs from the requested type (e.g. a bitmap of the document instead of the document itself in cases where the client is not expected to have a viewer application for the requested type, such as PCL or AFP)

- pdfaValidationResult: validation result in the form of an XML report; This output is only expected for PDF/A preview processes.

#### XSL-FO
![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 39. XSL-FO*

Contains settings for the XSL-FO creation:

- Show XSL-FO Preview: Activate the preview for XSL-FO.

- Infinica-Ressources: Path to the Infinica resources.

- Content for empty blocks: Many renders ignore empty blocks. With this setting it is possible to fill empty blocks automatically with any content. This way the renderer does not ignore them. A non-breaking space is a good choice, since they are invisible and are not trimmed (Copy the character from somewhere else).

- Process assertions: Defines if assertions should be transformed. Possible choices are:

Always

- Auto

- Never

- Initializion of meta data: Determines how the default value for the meta data is calculated for the XSL transformation.

#### XSL-IDX
![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 40. XSL-IDX*

Contains settings for the XSL-IDX creation:

- Show XSL-IDX Preview: Activate the preview for XSL-IDX.

- Infinica-Ressources: Path to the Infinica resources.

- Content for empty blocks: Many renders ignore empty blocks. With this setting it is possible to fill empty blocks automatically with any content. This way the renderer does not ignore them. A non-breaking space is a good choice, since they are invis-ible and are not trimmed (Copy the character from somewhere else).

- Process assertions: Defines if assertions should be transformed. Possible choices are:

Always

- Auto

- Never

- Initializion of meta data: Determines how the default value for the meta data is calculated for the XSL transformation.

## Various
### Show/Hide Grid
**Usage**: Toolbar

Switches the *grid *in the *Designer *tab of the *Main *view on and off

### Show/Hide Labels
**Usage**: Toolbar

Shows or hides element labels in the *Designer *tab in order to be able to gain a better overview about the template. When labels are hidden, information like *Template Part References *and *Conditions *are not shown anymore, so the *Desiger *tab should look a bit more like the generated output document.

### Show/Hide Control Characters
**Usage**: Toolbar

This icon switches the *pilcrow *in the *Designer *tab of the *Main *view on and off

### Reload/Refresh Preview
**Usage**: Toolbar

Inside the *Designer *view, this action updates the file (closed and reopened). Therefore, the document has to be saved previously. When the preview tab is opened, the output is regenerated.
